    body: "It didn't feel real until I saw it on the faces around me.\n\nI knew the word, and the grade, and what the grade meant. None of it landed. I sat with the worst news a person gets and felt, mostly, nothing — the way you don't feel a cut until you look down. Then I looked at my mother. And my sister. And I saw the thing happening to them, in their faces, plain, and that was when it reached me. I was the one it was happening to. I was the cancer kid. I sobbed.\n\nRay held the clippers. Before he started, my best friend Erik asked if he could keep a slice of it — a lock of hair, half a joke, the kind of thing you say to keep a room from going heavy. I thought it was funny. Then Ray turned the clippers on and the yard went so still that we both forgot. Nobody took the slice. It was supposed to be light. Somewhere in the sound of the clippers it stopped being light.\n\nHair you're going to lose anyway, taken on your own terms, in a yard, is a strange small mercy. You decide one thing in a year where you decide nothing.\n\nSomewhere in there I made myself a rule. I gave myself permission to cry up to five times a day.\n\nIt sounds like a joke and it wasn't. A man my age, raised the way men are raised, doesn't have a place to put that much grief. So I built one. Five was not a limit to stay under; it was a door I was allowed to walk through, five times, no questions, no apology. I never used all five. It mattered that they were there.\n\nI don't romanticize any of it. Cancer is not a teacher. It is not a gift. It doesn't come into your life for a reason. What it does is end the version of you that thought time was a thing you owned. What you build after — the rules, the scale, the doors you give yourself — that part is yours. That part you write.\n\nI gave a frightened young man permission to cry five times a day. It's one of the few things from that year I'd do exactly the same.",
