    body: "At the end of a show in 2019 I told the room, half-joking, \"If you want to see how this whole thing goes, I guess you'll have to come to the show we do here in four years.\"\n\nI had no idea if I'd make it. It was the kind of thing you say to keep an audience from feeling the weight of what they'd just watched — a one-year-after-the-diagnosis show, storytelling and magic and mind-reading, built around the fact that a year earlier I'd been told to say goodbye. My neurosurgeon had called making it as far as I had a literal miracle. So I made the room a promise I wasn't sure I could keep, and then I went and tried to keep it.\n\nFour years later we were all in a Smokey Bones. About fifty people. It was my cancer-free day — the day \"in remission\" officially became \"cancer free.\" I wrote in my journal that morning, plainly: _Happy Cancer Free Day. Holy shit is it liberating. I'm no longer a cancer kid. I'm visually impaired, but I'm out. I'm in the survivor club._\n\nWhat I keep coming back to isn't the milestone. It's the people. When I was twenty-two and dying and uninsured, people I'd never have asked insisted on helping. They gave time — driving me to appointments. They gave money — cash, gift cards so there was gas in the car to get to treatment. People who chose to stay anonymous. All they asked in return was to know that if I lost, I'd tried everything to win.\n\nBecause of them, I won.\n\nI wrote this the day it became official, and it's still the truest thing I know about that year: _It still doesn't feel real as I type this._ It still doesn't. You don't get to feel a miracle the way you feel a cut. You just get to keep showing up to the shows you promised you'd do.",
