    published: true,
    excerpt: "I don't sell death. I sell the safety net.",
    body: "I don't sell death. I sell the safety net.\n\nFor twenty years my work was wonder — making a room believe, for a few seconds, that the world is more permeable than it looks. Now I sell health and life insurance, and people sometimes raise an eyebrow at the turn, as if the magician had traded the dream for a desk. It took me a while to understand that it wasn't a retreat from the dream at all. It's the most honest work anyone's ever handed me.\n\nHere's why I can do it without flinching. At twenty-two I was uninsured when the worst thing came true. The options in front of me were not good and not many: dying, or filing for bankruptcy. Those were the two doors. I know exactly what it is to face the end of your life and find that nobody made sure you were covered — to do the math on survival from a hospital bed and come up with two answers, both of them ruin.\n\nI made it across. A program ended up covering me after the fact, and the debt that should have followed me for the rest of my life was wiped out. I got lucky. Not everyone does. So now I do one thing: I make sure the people I talk to never have to stand in front of those two doors. That's the whole job. Not death — the net under the worst day of a person's life, so that surviving it doesn't cost them everything they have left.\n\nA magician selling insurance sounds like a punchline. It's the least flashy and most honest thing I do. I'd been to the place this work exists to prevent, and I came back, and I'd rather spend my days making sure fewer people ever have to go there at all.",
