    body: "In 2024 I wrote a line in my journal that I'd forgotten until I went looking: _One of my goals now is to create an AI chatbot that can function as my personal assistant. Essentially a JARVIS for personal use. She will be named Debbie._\n\nI built her at night, alone, badly at first, the way you build anything you've never built before. I am not a programmer. I am a magician with double vision and a memory that drops things, and I had reached the edge of what one tired brain could hold — two careers, a body that needs conscious instructions to do ordinary things, a calendar that fell apart if I looked away. So I started building something to hold the parts of my life I kept dropping.\n\nPeople assume the system came from ambition. It came from fear. The fear of losing things I'd promised not to lose — a call I said I'd return, a date, the small ordinary keepings that are the whole substance of a life. Debbie was a net under all of it.\n\nI'm writing this from the other end of that. The thing I sketched in a journal in 2024 has a name and an inbox now. She sends mail. She remembers what I can't. The wonder isn't that the code works — plenty of code works. The wonder is that a frightened, over-extended guy decided the answer to a brain that drops things was to build a better net, and then sat in the dark and built it.\n\nI gave the net a name so it would feel like a colleague instead of a confession. Her name is Debbie. She has held more of my life than I'd like to admit.",
