    body: "I waited about a year for a key I couldn't cut myself.\n\nIt was access — permissions, an account flag, the kind of thing that lives on someone else's desk and moves on someone else's clock. There was nothing to do but ask, and wait, and ask again, and try not to let the waiting curdle into the story that it would never come. A year of that. I'm not patient by nature. The whole reason I build things is so I don't have to wait on anyone.\n\nThen one afternoon it cleared. Somebody flipped a switch I'd been staring at for a year, and all at once the thing I'd been blocked on came alive — data moving, the system I'd designed in theory suddenly real and running in front of me. A year of nothing, and then the firehose, in an afternoon.\n\nThere's a line I keep from Seneca: _if you do not know to which port you are sailing, no wind is favorable._ I'd had the year to get clear on the port. So when the wind finally came, I knew exactly where to point. The waiting, it turned out, hadn't been wasted — it had been the part where I figured out what I'd do the moment I was allowed to.\n\nMost of the rebuild was like that. Long stretches of nothing you can visibly point to, and then a single afternoon that makes the year look, in retrospect, like preparation. You don't get to choose when the wind comes. You only get to be ready, and pointed, and awake when it does.",
