    body: "For a magician, \"the man behind the curtain\" is the part you're never supposed to see. For three years, I couldn't stand him.\n\nAfter the divorce, after the worst of the rebuild, I'd catch myself in a quiet moment and not like the person running the machine — the one behind my own curtain, making the calls, keeping the promises or not. I'd survived cancer. I'd survived the marriage. I had not, somewhere in there, kept myself good company. You can outlast enormous things and still not be able to sit alone in a room with who you've become.\n\nIt took three years. I wrote it down on an ordinary morning, almost in passing, and only noticed afterward how big it was: _it took three years, but I finally like the person behind the curtain again._\n\nThere was no event. No breakthrough I can point to and sell you. It accrued, the way trust accrues — one kept promise at a time, until the person making them stops feeling like a stranger you're stuck with. The same morning I wrote that, I wrote the proof, and it's almost embarrassing how small the proof is: _I'm cancer-free and showing up every day. I am tired this morning, but I got up._\n\nThat's it. That's the whole turn. Not a triumph — a tired man who got up, and who, after three years, didn't mind the company of the one who made him.\n\nThe audience never sees behind the curtain. But I live back there. It matters, more than I expected, whether I can stand the man I find.",
