    body: "There's a proverb I keep coming back to: better to be a warrior in a garden than a gardener in a war. The capacity to be dangerous, and choosing not to be — that's the version of strength I actually want. Not to do harm. To be able to protect the people I love, and to choose peace from a place of capacity instead of a place of helplessness.\n\nI'm not there yet, and the gap shows up in the most ordinary place: the mirror. I make excuses about the gym. I build things, I move fast intellectually, I can put a company together in my head — and then I catch my own reflection and don't fully respect the man looking back. I've written it more plainly than I'd like: _I'm afraid I spend the rest of my life not respecting the man I see in the mirror._\n\nThe body is just where it's visible. The real fear is underneath, and it isn't about muscle. It's that I never reach a place where I deeply respect myself — and that, because I don't, I let other people disrespect me, and call it being easygoing, for the rest of my life.\n\nI survived the thing that was supposed to kill me. You'd think that would settle the question of self-respect for good. It doesn't. Surviving proved I could endure. It didn't prove I could stand in a room and take up the space I'm entitled to. Those are different muscles. I'm working the first one. I'm still learning the second.\n\nA warrior in a garden. Capable, and gentle by choice, not by default. That's the man I'm trying to become behind the curtain — not someone who can hurt people, someone who no longer quietly agrees to be hurt.",
