    excerpt: "I owed someone a piece of work for months, and the not-doing of it had grown heavier than the work could ever have been.",
    body: "I owed someone a piece of work for months, and the not-doing of it had grown heavier than the work could ever have been.\n\nIt was footage — a reel I'd promised to send, the kind of small professional thing that takes an afternoon. I didn't send it for an afternoon. Then I didn't send it for a great many afternoons, and somewhere in there it stopped being a task and became a verdict. The footage was bad. I'd waited too long. Sending it now would only document how long I'd waited. I built that case against myself carefully — the way you build the thing you most want to believe.\n\nI was in a cabin in Norway when I finally sat down to face it. The first real stillness I'd let myself have in years, and what I did with it was open the thing I'd been most afraid of.\n\nThe story came apart in stages. First: *the footage is trash.* I pushed on that — trash how? — and underneath the global verdict found a narrow, real critique: it didn't match what the person I was sending it to would want to see. Specific. Fixable. Not a death sentence. Then the second story surfaced, smaller and stupider and truer: I didn't actually know where the footage *was.* On the drive? Back home? I had spent months ashamed of the quality of a file I wasn't sure still existed.\n\nSo I searched the drive. And there it was — the finished reel, four hundred megabytes of it, sitting at the root, exactly the thing I'd been telling myself I had failed to make. It had been done the whole time. I'd been carrying the weight of something that was already sitting on the far side of the very wall I wouldn't walk up to.\n\nI sent it. I didn't grovel. I wrote: *I have a fantastic laundry list of beautiful excuses I'd be happy to walk you through. (I'm highly skeptical there will be interest.)*\n\nThe reply came eighty-two seconds later. *Amazing, I will let you know. Enjoy your vacation.*\n\nEighty-two seconds. I had carried that thing for months and it cost her a minute and a half and not one ounce of the judgment I'd assigned her. I sat in the cabin and felt the obscene disproportion of it — everything I'd paid against what it turned out to be worth.\n\nHere is what I took, and what I take everywhere now. The dread is almost never about the task. The task is usually small, and often already done. The dread is a story you tell instead of opening the drive — and the story is the only heavy thing in the room. Inventory before you despair. Walk up to the wall and check whether it's even there.\n\nAnd the people you've cast as your judges, on the other side of the thing you can't make yourself do — most of them are just waiting, kindly, to say: *amazing, enjoy your vacation.*",
