    published: true,
    excerpt: "Most of the walls I run into turn out to be painted on.",
    body: "Most of the walls I run into turn out to be painted on.\n\nI have a pattern I've only recently learned to catch. Faced with something I need to do, I decide first that I have to figure out some hard prerequisite — _I can't do this until I've solved that_ — and the prerequisite becomes a wall, and the wall becomes a reason the whole thing sits untouched for weeks. Then one day I actually walk up to the wall, and there's nothing there. The hard prerequisite was a sentence I made up. The real task was small, and cheap, and had been doable the entire time.\n\nIt happened twice in one sitting recently. Two things I'd parked for weeks, each behind a story about how complicated it would be to start. I looked directly at them and both stories evaporated in about a minute. The fix, in both cases, was the obvious small thing I'd been walking around for a month.\n\nWhat struck me wasn't shame. It was relief. _I thought it was more complicated than that._ Once you see the wall is paint, the move is obvious, and you almost laugh.\n\nI think this is a survivor's habit, or at least it's mine. When you've been through something genuinely enormous, your nervous system gets calibrated for enormous. It starts pre-loading difficulty onto things that don't have any — building a cathedral of complication around a task that needed a screwdriver. The story gets heavy so the doing never starts.\n\nThe line I wrote that morning is the one I want tattooed somewhere I'll see it: **the work was lighter than the story.** Almost always. The story is the weight. The work is usually just the obvious small thing, waiting for you to walk up and find the wall was paint.",
